jumpingJacks.title: JUMPING JACKS
jumpingJacks.instructions:
Start with your feet together and your arms by your sides, then jump up with your feet apart and your hands overhead.

Return to the start position then do the next rep. This exercise provides a full-body workout and works all your large muscle groups.

1.title: Landing too hard
1.description: When you jump in the air and come down, you are putting too much impact or pressure on your feet, ankles, knees or other joints, this can lead to discomfort or injury. Try to land on the balls of your feet rather than your heels. It absorbs more shock.

2.title: Not keeping the knees bent
2.description: Failing to keep the knees bent can cause the exercise to be less effective.

3.title: Not engaging the core
3.description: It requires the core muscles to be engaged throughout the exercise. If the core is not engaged, it can lead to poor form and an ineffective workout.

breathingTips.1: Inhale as you jump your feet apart.
breathingTips.2: Exhale as you jump your feet back together.
breathingTips.3: Take deep breaths to fully oxygenate your body.

pushUp.title: PUSH UP
pushUp.instructions:
Start with your feet together and your arms by your sides, then jump up with your feet apart and your hands overhead.

Return to the start position then do the next rep. This exercise provides a full-body workout and works all your large muscle groups.

1.title: Landing too hard
1.description: When you jump in the air and come down, you are putting too much impact or pressure on your feet, ankles, knees or other joints, this can lead to discomfort or injury. Try to land on the balls of your feet rather than your heels. It absorbs more shock.

2.title: Not keeping the knees bent
2.description: Failing to keep the knees bent can cause the exercise to be less effective.

3.title: Not engaging the core
3.description: It requires the core muscles to be engaged throughout the exercise. If the core is not engaged, it can lead to poor form and an ineffective workout.

breathingTips.1: Inhale as you jump your feet apart.
breathingTips.2: Exhale as you jump your feet back together.
breathingTips.3: Take deep breaths to fully oxygenate your body.

abdominalCrunches.title: ABDOMINAL CRUNCHES
abdominalCrunches.instructions:
Lie on your back with your knees bent and your arms stretched forward.

Then lift your upper body off the floor. Hold for a few seconds and slowly return.

It primarily works the rectus abdominis muscle and the obliques.

1.title: Pulling your neck
1.description: Pulling your neck during Abdominal Crunches can strain your neck and lead to potential injury. Instead, use your core muscles to lift your upper body.

2.title: Not engaging the core
2.description: It requires the core muscles to be engaged throughout the entire exercise. If the core is not engaged, it can lead to poor form and an ineffective workout.

3.title: Performing the exercise too quickly or with poor form
3.description: This can increase the risk of injury and make the exercise less effective.

breathingTips.1: Proper breathing during Abdominal Crunches is important because it helps engage the core muscles and provides stability for the spine.
breathingTips.2: Exhaling as you lift your torso off the ground helps engage the upper abdominals, which are the primary muscles targeted in this exercise.
breathingTips.3: Inhaling as you lower back down helps you maintain control and avoid straining your back

inclinePushUp.title: INCLINE PUSH UP
inclinePushUp.instructions:
Start in the regular push-up position but with your hands elevated on a chair or bench.

Then push your body up down using your arm strength.

Remember to keep your body straight.

1.title: Improper hand placement
1.description: Placing your hands too wide or too close together can put unnecessary strain on your elbows and wrists. Keep you hands shoulder-width apart and directly under your shoulders.

2.title: Excessive lifting of the hips or collapsing of the back
2.description: Allowing your back to sag or lifting your hips too high during Push-ups can put undue stress on your spine and increase the risk of injury. Keep your body in a straight line form head to heels.

3.title: Not engaging the core
3.description: It requires the core muscles to be engaged throughout the entire exercise. If the core is not engaged, it can lead to poor form and an ineffective workout.

4.title: Allowing the elbows to flare out of the sides
4.description: This can put unnecessary stress on the shoulder joints and can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise.

breathingTips.1: Inhale as you lower your body towards the elevated surface.
breathingTips.2: Exhale as you push your body back up to the starting position.

legRaises.title: LEG RAISES
legRaises.instructions:
Lie down on your back, and put your hands beneath your hips for support.

Then lift your legs up until they form a right angle with the floor.

Slowly bring your legs back down and repeat the exercise.

1.title: Raising the legs too high
1.description: This can cause excessive bending of the lower back and increase the risk of injury.

2.title: Not controlling the legs
2.description: This can result in improper form, and reduced effectiveness of the exercise.

3.title: Excessive reliance on leg strength
3.description: Excessive reliance on leg strength during exercise while ignoring the participation of core muscle groups will affect the exercise effect.

4.title: Lack of support for the lower back
4.description: This can damage the spine. You can avoid the risk of injury by placing a folded towel under your lower back.

breathingTips.1: Proper breathing during leg raises is important because it helps activate the core muscles, improve the effectiveness of the exercise, and protect your spine from injury.
breathingTips.2: Exhaling as you raise your legs helps you better control the movement.
breathingTips.3: Inhaling as you lower them reduces the stress on your spine.

mountainClimber.title: MOUNTAIN CLIMBER
mountainClimber.instructions:
Start in the push-up position. Bend your right knee towards your chest and keep your left leg straight, then quickly switch from one leg to the other.

This exercise strengthens multiple muscle groups.

1.title: Hunching the back
1.description: Hunching the back can put undue stress on your spine and increase the risk of injury. Keep your core engaged and your back straight.

2.title: Lifting the hips
2.description: Raising the hips too high during the exercise can cause the lower back to arch and can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise.

3.title: Moving too quickly
3.description: Performing the exercise too quickly can reduce its effectiveness and may cause you to lose proper form.

4.title: Not engaging the core
4.description: It requires the core muscles to be engaged throughout the entire exercise. If the core is not engaged, it can lead to poor form and an ineffective workout.

breathingTips.1: Take natural and deep breaths. Avoid holding your breath.
breathingTips.2: Keep a consistent breathing rhythm throughout the exercise.

wideArmPushUp.title: WIDE ARM PUSH UP
wideArmPushUp.instructions:
Start in the regular push-up position but with your hands spread wider than your shoulders.

Then push your body up and down. Remember to keep your body straight.

1.title: Allowing the elbows to flare out of the sides
1.description: This places unnecessary stress on the shoulder joints and can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise.

2.title: Failing to engage the core muscles
2.description: This can cause the lower back to sag and increase the risk of injury. Tighten your abs to engage the core muscles.

3.title: Excessive lifting of the hips or collapsing of the back
3.description: Allowing your back to sag or lifting your hips too high during Push-ups can put undue stress on your spine and increase the risk of injury. Keep your body in a straight line form head to heels.

4.title: Not keeping the head in a neutral position
4.description: This can cause strain on the neck and also take away from the effectiveness of the exercise.

breathingTips.1: Inhale as you lower your body towards the ground.
breathingTips.2: Exhale as you push your body back up to the starting position.
breathingTips.3: Taking deep breaths throughout an exercise can increase oxygen flow to your muscles, which helps them work more efficiently and can help enhance your performance.

kneePushUp.title: KNEE PUSH UP
kneePushUp.instructions:
Start in the regular push-up position, then let your knees touch the floor and raise your feet up off the floor.

Next push your body up and down.

1.title: Improper hand placement
1.description: Placing your hands too wide or too close together can put unnecessary strain on your elbows and wrists. Keep you hands shoulder-width apart and directly under your shoulders.

2.title: Not engaging the core
2.description: It requires the core muscles to be engaged throughout the entire exercise. If the core is not engaged, it can lead to poor form and an ineffective workout.

3.title: Excessive lifting of the hips or collapsing of the back
3.description: Allowing your back to sag or lifting your hips too high during Push-ups can put undue stress on your spine and increase the risk of injury. Keep your body in a straight line form head to heels.

4.title: Allowing the elbows to flare out of the sides
4.description: This places unnecessary stress on the shoulder joints and can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise.

breathingTips.1: Inhale as you lower your body towards the ground.
breathingTips.2: Exhale as you push your body back up to the starting position.
breathingTips.3: Its important to keep your breathing steady and controlled throughout the exercise to maintain good form and prevent dizziness.

squat.title: SQUAT
squat.instructions:
Stand with your feet shoulder width apart and your arms stretched forward, then lower your body until your thighs are parallel with the floor.

Your knees should be extended in the same direction as your toes. Return to the start position and do the next rep.

This works the thighs, hips buttocks, quads, hamstrings and lower body.

1.title: Allowing your knees to cave in
1.description: This can put unnecessary stress on the knee joint and increase the risk of injury. Keep your knees in line with your toes. Also, do not let your knees go past your toes.

2.title: Hunching the back
2.description: Hunching the back can put undue stress on your spine and increase the risk of injury. Keep your core engaged and your back straight.

3.title: Not going low enough
3.description: If you don't squat low enough, you're not engaging your glutes and hamstrings as effectively. Aim to squat until your thighs are parallel to the ground.

4.title: Letting your heels come off the ground
4.description: Lifting your heels can shift your weight forward and put more stress on your knees. Keep your feet flat on the ground.

breathingTips.1: Inhale as you lower your body down.
breathingTips.2: Exhale as you push yourself back up.
breathingTips.3: This can help to stabilize your core and ensure proper form.

cobraStretch.title: COBRA STRETCH
cobraStretch.instructions:
Lie down on your stomach and bend your elbows with your hands beneath your shoulders.

Then push your chest up off the ground as far as possible. Hold this position for seconds.

1.title: Overarching the back
1.description: One common mistake is over-arching the neck during the exercise, which can lead to neck strain or injury. Instead, keep the neck in a neutral position and focus on engaging the muscles of the upper back to lift the chest off the ground.

2.title: Using the arms to lift the chest
2.description: Another mistake is using the arms to lift the chest, which can put unnecessary strain on the shoulders and arms. Instead, focus on using the muscles of the upper back to lift the chest off the ground.

3.title: Shrugging and tucking in the chest
3.description: When the upper body is raised, shrugging and tucking in the chest will increase the pressure on the elbow joints and prevent the upper back muscles from being well stretched.

breathingTips.1: Breathe deeply before you begin the stretch can help prepare your body.
breathingTips.2: Focus on your breath and keep it steady and even throughout the stretch. Holding your breath can cause tension and discomfort.

lumbarTwist.title: SPINE LUMBAR TWIST STRETCH
lumbarTwist.instructions:
Lie on your back with your legs extended.

Exhale, lift your left leg up and use your right hand to pull your left knee to the right. Keep your other arm extended to the side on the floor.

Breathe naturally. Hold this position for a few seconds.

1.title: Using momentum to force the twist
1.description: This can lead to excessive strain on the spine and may cause injuries. Instead, focus on a controlled and gradual movement.

2.title: Overstretching
2.description: Twisting the spine beyond its natural range of motion can cause discomfort or injury. It is important to listen to your body and only twist as far as is comfortable.

3.title: Lifting the back off the floor
3.description: When doing this exercise, the back should remain flat on the floor. Lifting the back can place too much pressure on the lower back, causing potential injury.

4.title: Not keeping the shoulders on the ground
4.description: Try to keep your shoulders on the ground while doing this exercise. Lifting shoulders can decrease the effectiveness of the stretch and potentially cause injury.

breathingTips.1: Breathe deeply before you begin the stretch can help prepare your body.
breathingTips.2: Focus on your breath and keep it steady and even throughout the stretch. Holding your breath can cause tension and discomfort.

doorwayStretch.title: Doorway Stretch
doorwayStretch.instructions:
Find a doorway, take a lunge position in the doorway with your arms on the doorframe and your elbows a little lower than your shoulders, then slowly bring your chest forward.

Hold this position for 30-40 seconds. Then slowly come out of it, bring your arms down and do a couple of shoulder rolls.

Don't pull your head forward, and keep your neck relaxed.

1.title: Arching the lower back
1.description: Arching the lower back can make the stretch feel deeper. However, this can put unnecessary strain on the lower back and may cause discomfort or injury.

2.title: Shrugging the shoulders
2.description: This can cause tension in the neck and upper back, which can lead to discomfort or injury. It's important to keep your shoulders relaxed and down.

3.title: Overstretching
3.description: Push yourself properly in a chest stretch but do not overdo it. Overstretching can cause injury and may even make the muscles tighter.

4.title: Holding the stretch too long
4.description: Holding a chest stretch for too long can actually cause the muscle to tighten up again, undoing the work you just did. It's best to hold the stretch for about 15-30 seconds.

breathingTips.1: Inhale deeply and slowly, feeling your chest expand.
breathingTips.2: Exhale slowly, feeling your chest contract.

sitUp.title: SIT UP
sitUp.instructions:
Lie on your back with your knees bent and your feet flat on the floor. Place your hands behind your head or cross them over your chest.

Engage your core and lift your upper body towards your knees. Lower back down to the starting position and repeat.

1.title: Pulling on the neck
1.description: Using your hands to pull your neck can strain your neck muscles. Instead, use your core muscles to lift your upper body.

2.title: Not engaging the core
2.description: Failing to engage the core can lead to poor form and reduce the effectiveness of the exercise.

3.title: Using momentum
3.description: Relying on momentum rather than muscle strength can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise and increase the risk of injury.

4.title: Arching the lower back
4.description: Arching the lower back can put unnecessary strain on the spine. Keep your back straight and engage your core.

breathingTips.1: Exhale as you lift your upper body towards your knees.
breathingTips.2: Inhale as you lower back down to the starting position.
breathingTips.3: Maintain a steady and controlled breathing pattern throughout the exercise.

reverseLunges.title: REVERSE LUNGES
reverseLunges.instructions:
Stand upright with your feet shoulder-width apart. Step backward with your right foot and lower your body until your left thigh is parallel to the floor and your right knee is almost touching the ground.

Return to the starting position and repeat with the other leg.

1.title: Letting the front knee go past the toes
1.description: This can put unnecessary stress on the knee joint and increase the risk of injury. Keep your front knee in line with your toes.

2.title: Not keeping the torso upright
2.description: Leaning forward can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise and put strain on your lower back. Keep your torso upright and engage your core.

3.title: Not stepping back far enough
3.description: Failing to step back far enough can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise. Make sure to step back far enough so that your back knee is almost touching the ground.

4.title: Not engaging the core
4.description: It requires the core muscles to be engaged throughout the entire exercise. If the core is not engaged, it can lead to poor form and an ineffective workout.

breathingTips.1: Inhale as you step back and lower your body.
breathingTips.2: Exhale as you push yourself back up to the starting position.
breathingTips.3: Maintain a steady and controlled breathing pattern throughout the exercise.

burpee.title: BURPEE
burpee.instructions: Start in a standing position. Drop into a squat with your hands on the ground. Kick your feet back into a plank position. Perform a push-up. Return your feet to the squat position. Jump up from the squat position and reach your arms overhead.

1.title: Skipping the push-up
1.description: Skipping the push-up can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise. Make sure to include the push-up to engage your upper body muscles.

2.title: Not jumping high enough
2.description: Failing to jump high enough can reduce the intensity of the exercise. Aim to jump as high as you can to maximize the benefits.

3.title: Letting the hips sag during the plank
3.description: Allowing your hips to sag during the plank can put unnecessary strain on your lower back. Keep your body in a straight line from head to heels.

4.title: Not engaging the core
4.description: It requires the core muscles to be engaged throughout the entire exercise. If the core is not engaged, it can lead to poor form and an ineffective workout.

breathingTips.1: Inhale as you drop into the squat and kick your feet back.
breathingTips.2: Exhale as you perform the push-up.
breathingTips.3: Inhale as you return your feet to the squat position.
breathingTips.4: Exhale as you jump up and reach your arms overhead.

crunch.title: CRUNCH
crunch.instructions:
Lie on your back with your knees bent and your feet flat on the floor. Place your hands behind your head or cross them over your chest.

Engage your core and lift your upper body towards your knees. Lower back down to the starting position and repeat.

1.title: Pulling on the neck
1.description: Using your hands to pull your neck can strain your neck muscles. Instead, use your core muscles to lift your upper body.

2.title: Not engaging the core
2.description: Failing to engage the core can lead to poor form and reduce the effectiveness of the exercise.

3.title: Using momentum
3.description: Relying on momentum rather than muscle strength can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise and increase the risk of injury.

4.title: Arching the lower back
4.description: Arching the lower back can put unnecessary strain on the spine. Keep your back straight and engage your core.

breathingTips.1: Exhale as you lift your upper body towards your knees.
breathingTips.2: Inhale as you lower back down to the starting position.
breathingTips.3: Maintain a steady and controlled breathing pattern throughout the exercise.

kneelingSquat.title: KNEELING SQUAT
kneelingSquat.instructions: Start by kneeling on the floor with your knees hip-width apart and your toes pointed behind you. Sit back onto your heels, then engage your glutes and thighs to lift your hips up until your body forms a straight line from your shoulders to your knees. Lower back down to the starting position and repeat.

1.title: Not engaging the glutes
1.description: Failing to engage the glutes can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise and put unnecessary strain on the lower back.

2.title: Arching the lower back
2.description: Arching the lower back can put unnecessary strain on the spine. Keep your back straight and engage your core.

3.title: Not keeping the knees aligned
3.description: Allowing the knees to flare out or come too close together can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise and increase the risk of injury. Keep your knees aligned with your hips.

breathingTips.1: Inhale as you sit back onto your heels.
breathingTips.2: Exhale as you lift your hips up to the starting position.
breathingTips.3: Maintain a steady and controlled breathing pattern throughout the exercise.

plankLunges.title: PLANK LUNGES
plankLunges.instructions: Start in a plank position with your hands directly under your shoulders and your body in a straight line from head to heels. Step your right foot forward to the outside of your right hand, then return to the plank position. Repeat with your left foot.

1.title: Letting the hips sag
1.description: Allowing your hips to sag can put unnecessary strain on your lower back. Keep your body in a straight line from head to heels.

2.title: Not engaging the core
2.description: Failing to engage the core can lead to poor form and reduce the effectiveness of the exercise.

3.title: Not stepping far enough forward
3.description: Failing to step far enough forward can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise. Make sure to step your foot all the way to the outside of your hand.

4.title: Rushing the movement
4.description: Performing the exercise too quickly can reduce its effectiveness and may cause you to lose proper form.

breathingTips.1: Inhale as you step your foot forward.
breathingTips.2: Exhale as you return to the plank position.
breathingTips.3: Maintain a steady and controlled breathing pattern throughout the exercise.

reverseCrunch.title: REVERSE CRUNCH
reverseCrunch.instructions: Lie on your back with your hands by your sides or under your hips for support. Bend your knees and lift your legs so your thighs are perpendicular to the floor. Use your lower abs to lift your hips off the floor and bring your knees towards your chest. Lower back down to the starting position and repeat.

1.title: Using momentum
1.description: Relying on momentum rather than muscle strength can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise and increase the risk of injury. Focus on using your lower abs to lift your hips.

2.title: Not engaging the core
2.description: Failing to engage the core can lead to poor form and reduce the effectiveness of the exercise.

3.title: Arching the lower back
3.description: Arching the lower back can put unnecessary strain on the spine. Keep your back flat on the floor and engage your core.

4.title: Lifting the upper body
4.description: Lifting your upper body off the floor can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise. Keep your upper body relaxed and focus on lifting your hips.

breathingTips.1: Exhale as you lift your hips off the floor.
breathingTips.2: Inhale as you lower back down to the starting position.
breathingTips.3: Maintain a steady and controlled breathing pattern throughout the exercise.

sideLunge.title: SIDE LUNGE
sideLunge.instructions: Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart. Take a big step to the side with your right foot, bending your right knee and pushing your hips back while keeping your left leg straight. Return to the starting position and repeat on the other side.

1.title: Not stepping wide enough
1.description: Failing to step wide enough can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise. Make sure to take a big step to the side.

2.title: Letting the knee go past the toes
2.description: This can put unnecessary stress on the knee joint and increase the risk of injury. Keep your knee in line with your toes.

3.title: Not keeping the torso upright
3.description: Leaning forward can reduce the effectiveness of the exercise and put strain on your lower back. Keep your torso upright and engage your core.

4.title: Not engaging the core
4.description: It requires the core muscles to be engaged throughout the entire exercise. If the core is not engaged, it can lead to poor form and an ineffective workout.

breathingTips.1: Inhale as you step to the side and lower your body.
breathingTips.2: Exhale as you push yourself back up to the starting position.
breathingTips.3: Maintain a steady and controlled breathing pattern throughout the exercise.
